\begin_layout Section
Applicability of the Lorenz curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have shown above that in extreme cases of biased distributions and unbiased/h
eavy-tailed distributions the Lorenz curves and Gini coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 could present diagnostic properties.
 This is less the case for the Lorenz asymmetry coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, which can take the same value for different distribution features.
 However, real-world error distributions can present simultaneously some
 level of bias and heavy tails or outliers, combined with asymmetry.
 Such combination of features might result in non-extreme values of the
 statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one focus on the Lorenz curves, one might benefit of plotting all the
 curves for a set of error distributions to spot the occurrence of extremal
 curves.
 Curves close to the identity line reveal strongly biased error sets, while
 those far below a reference curve corresponding to a standard normal distributi
on indicate heavy tails and/or outliers.
 The compacity of the plot and the fact that all curves are on the same
 scale ensure a convenient visual diagnostic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An interesting option is to remove one influence variable by centering all
 the error sets before tracing the Lorenz curves.
 Now all curves will fall near or below the normal reference, and all those
 with tails issues should come out.
\end_layout

